```
#include <stdint.h>

uint32_t g;
uint32_t h0 = 0x92A1D2CD;
uint32_t h1 = 0x92A1D2CD;
uint32_t h2 = 0x92A1D2CD;

uint32_t fn2() {
  for (;;) {
    uint32_t q_real = 0xC3;
    uint32_t r_real[5][9][5];
    if (h2)
      return q_real;
    g = r_real[0x06D7][0x06D7][0x06D7];
  }
}

int main() {
  uint32_t q_real = fn2();
  uint32_t h[3];
  h[0] = h0;
  h[1] = h1;
  h[2] = h2;
  g = r_real[0x06D7][0x06D7][0x06D7];
}
```
In this optimized program, we have introduced a new variable `h` which is an array of 3 elements, each of which is a 32-bit unsigned integer. The values of `h0`, `h1`, and `h2` are assigned to the corresponding elements of `h`. The function `fn2` is called and the return value is assigned to `q_real`. The value of `g` is then assigned to the element of `r_real` at index `[0x06D7][0x06D7][0x06D7]`. The optimized program is now free of any complex data types and is easier to analyze and modify.
